(44, 5, 20, 44, 11, 14, 14, 'all the words of this life', 'Connection of Salvation Messages', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of speaking words that lead to salvation. Acts 5:20 mentions ''all the words of this life,'' while Acts 11:14 refers to ''words, whereby thou and all thy house shall be saved.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 21, 43, 8, 2, 2, 'entered into the temple early in the morning', 'Teaching in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize the act of teaching in the temple early in the morning. This connection highlights the significance of the temple as a place of instruction for both Jesus and the apostles.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 21, 19, 105, 22, 22, NULL, 'Teaching and Authority Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of teaching and authority in both passages. Acts 5:21 describes the apostles teaching in the temple, while Psalms 105:22 mentions teaching wisdom to senators, suggesting a parallel in the role of leaders in imparting knowledge.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 21, 40, 5, 22, 22, 'the council', 'Judgment and Council Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of judgment and the council. Acts 5:21 mentions the council being called, while Matthew 5:22 warns about being in danger of the council for anger. This connection highlights the seriousness of communal judgment in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 21, 42, 21, 37, 38, 'entered into the temple early in the morning', 'Teaching in the Temple', 'Both passages emphasize the act of teaching in the temple early in the morning. This connection highlights the continuity of teaching as a central activity for both the apostles and Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 21, 42, 22, 66, 66, 'called the council together', 'Council Gatherings in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of religious leaders for a council. In Acts, the high priest and council convene to address the apostles, while in Luke, the elders and chief priests gather to question Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 21, 43, 18, 35, 35, NULL, 'Connection of Authority and Betrayal', 'This connection highlights the role of the chief priests in both passages. In Acts, the high priest and council are involved in the arrest of the apostles, while in John, the chief priests deliver Jesus to Pilate, indicating a theme of betrayal by religious authorities.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 21, 44, 4, 5, 7, 'the high priest came, and they that were with him', 'Gathering of Rulers and Elders', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of the high priest and council to address the apostles. This connection highlights the ongoing conflict between the religious authorities and the early followers of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 23, 19, 2, 4, 4, 'found no man within', 'Divine Protection and Mockery', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine intervention where the prison is found secure yet empty, paralleling the Lord''s derision of earthly powers. Both passages emphasize the futility of human efforts against divine will.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 23, 19, 33, 10, 10, 'the keepers standing without before the doors', 'Divine Intervention in Imprisonment', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine intervention, as seen in Acts where the prison is found secure yet empty, paralleling Psalms which states the Lord nullifies the plans of the wicked. Both passages emphasize God''s power to thwart human intentions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 23, 20, 21, 30, 30, 'found no man within', 'Divine Authority and Human Limitations', 'This connection highlights the inability of human efforts to contain God''s will, as seen in Acts where the prison is found secure yet empty. Proverbs emphasizes that no wisdom or counsel can stand against the Lord''s purpose.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 23, 25, 3, 37, 37, NULL, 'Divine Authority and Control', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority, as both passages emphasize that events occur only under God''s command. Acts 5:23 illustrates the miraculous escape from prison, suggesting divine intervention, while Lamentations 3:37 questions the efficacy of human pronouncements without God''s will.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 23, 25, 3, 55, 58, NULL, 'Deliverance from Imprisonment', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine deliverance from confinement. Both passages depict individuals in dire situations, with Acts referencing a miraculous escape from prison and Lamentations expressing a plea for rescue from a dungeon.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 23, 27, 3, 11, 25, 'no man within', 'Divine Deliverance in Crisis', 'Both passages emphasize God''s ability to deliver His followers from perilous situations. In Acts, the apostles are freed from prison without harm, while in Daniel, Shadrach, Meshach, and Abed-nego are unharmed in the fiery furnace.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 23, 27, 6, 22, 24, 'no man within', 'Divine Protection in Adversity', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine intervention in both passages. In Acts, the prison is found secure with no prisoners inside, paralleling Daniel''s experience of being unharmed in the lions'' den due to God''s protection.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 24, 44, 4, 1, 1, 'the captain of the temple', 'Connection of Temple Authorities', 'Both passages emphasize the involvement of the high priest, the captain of the temple, and the chief priests. This connection highlights the ongoing tension between the apostles and the temple authorities.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 24, 44, 5, 26, 26, NULL, 'Fear of the People', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of the people. In Acts 5:24, the high priest and others doubt the implications of the apostles'' actions, while in Acts 5:26, the captain acts cautiously to avoid provoking the crowd.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 24, 23, 9, 7, 7, 'doubted of them whereunto this would grow', 'Connection of Governance and Doubt', 'This connection highlights the theme of governance and its implications. In Acts, the high priest and others doubt the growth of the apostles'' influence, while Isaiah speaks of the unending increase of governance and peace.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 24, 23, 53, 1, 2, 'doubted of them whereunto this would grow', 'Connection of Doubt and Belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of doubt in Acts 5:24, paralleling the question of belief in Isaiah 53:1. Both passages emphasize the struggle to recognize and accept the truth of God''s revelation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 24, 27, 2, 34, 35, 'doubted of them whereunto this would grow', 'Connection of Doubt and Destruction', 'This connection highlights the theme of doubt in Acts 5:24, where the high priest and others question the implications of the apostles'' actions. Similarly, in Daniel 2:34-35, the destruction of the image represents a significant turning point, suggesting that doubt can precede monumental change.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 24, 27, 2, 44, 45, 'doubted of them whereunto this would grow', 'Kingdom and Authority Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of doubt regarding the establishment of God''s kingdom. In Acts, the high priest and others doubt the implications of the apostles'' actions, paralleling the certainty of God''s kingdom in Daniel, which will ultimately prevail over all earthly powers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 24, 38, 6, 12, 13, 'whereunto this would grow', 'Connection of Growth and Temple', 'This connection highlights the theme of growth and the establishment of the temple. In Acts, the high priest and others doubt where this movement will grow, while Zechariah speaks of The BRANCH growing and building the temple of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 26, 44, 5, 13, 13, 'feared the people', 'Fear of the People', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s reaction to the apostles. In Acts 5:13, the people magnified the apostles, while in Acts 5:26, the captain and officers feared the people, indicating their influence and respect.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 26, 44, 4, 21, 21, NULL, 'Fear of the People', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of the people influencing the actions of the authorities. In Acts 5:26, the captain and officers act without violence due to their fear of the people, paralleling Acts 4:21 where the authorities let the apostles go because of the people''s glorification of God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 26, 40, 14, 5, 5, NULL, 'Fear of the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of the crowd influencing actions. In Acts, the captain avoids violence due to fear of the people, while in Matthew, Herod refrains from executing John the Baptist for the same reason.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 26, 40, 21, 26, 26, 'for they feared the people', 'Fear of the People', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of the people influencing actions. In Acts, the captain''s hesitation is due to fearing the people, similar to the fear expressed in Matthew regarding John the Baptist''s status.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 26, 42, 20, 6, 6, 'feared the people, lest they should have been stoned', 'Fear of the People', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of the people regarding potential violence. In Acts, the captain fears the people lest they should be stoned, while in Luke, the religious leaders fear the people will stone them if they deny John''s prophetic status.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 26, 42, 20, 19, 19, 'feared the people', 'Fear of the People', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of the people by religious leaders. In Acts, the captain and officers act cautiously due to this fear, while in Luke, the chief priests and scribes also fear the people''s reaction to Jesus'' words.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
